reviews.body:
@Bob-IT It looks like my review will be iterative. My first scan was high level. This time I was triggered by how you changed the handling of ui elements in the plugins. I don't think that's really optimal at this point and that prompted me to grok how all of this works together a bit more.

One thing that still eludes me in general is this: we have a gnc-main-window and several plugin pages that add menu items. How does the code know where to insert the menu items from these plugin pages ? Do you know ?

I would assume the same logic should be applicable for the menu items inserted by aqbanking and ofx.

@christopherlam It looks OK to me but am not sure about 'writable' but can not think of another word, the only other thing is split it to two functions.
gnc_account_sel_filter_placeholder_accts (GNCAccountSel *gas, gboolean filter);
gnc_account_sel_filter_hidden_accts (GNCAccountSel *gas, gboolean filter);
but maybe it could be 
gnc_account_sel_filter_read_only_accts (GNCAccountSel *gas, gboolean filter);

@christopherlam 
I have had a quick look and looks OK to me but I think there is a tree path free missing from gnc_ui_custom_report_edit_name.

As to your Alt-F4, I think you could do the following...

```c
void
custom_report_dialog_destroy_cb (GtkWidget* widget, gpointer data)
{
    CustomReportDialog *crd = data;
    empty_tree_model (gtk_tree_view_get_model(GTK_TREE_VIEW(crd->reportview)));
    g_free (crd);
}

void
custom_report_dialog_close_cb(GtkWidget* widget, gpointer data)
{
    CustomReportDialog *crd = data;
    gnc_save_window_size(GNC_PREFS_GROUP_REPORT_SAVED_CONFIGS, GTK_WINDOW(crd->dialog));
    gtk_widget_destroy (crd->dialog);
}
```
and then connect the 'destroy' signal of the dialog to the destroy function in the glade file.
